<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="103" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,594,1267]" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,954,979]" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">Remarks.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[322,473,954,979]" pageId="2" pageNumber="103" refId="ref16205" refString="Sweet, M. H. (1996) The Evolution of the Haustorioidea of the World, and Post-Embryonic Development, Taxonomy and Ecology of the Haustoriidae (Amphipoda: Crustacea). Texas A &amp; M University, College Station, 640 pp. [PhD thesis]" type="book">Sweet (1996)</bibRefCitation>
proposed dividing 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Muller" authorityYear="1775" box="[692,817,956,979]" class="Malacostraca" family="Haustoriidae" genus="Haustorius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[692,817,956,979]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">Haustorius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
into two separate genera on either side of the Atlantic, and reclassified 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bousfield" baseAuthorityYear="1962" box="[343,507,990,1015]" class="Malacostraca" family="Haustoriidae" genus="Haustorius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="canadensis">
<emphasis box="[343,507,990,1015]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">H. canadensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as ‘Genus one 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bousfield" baseAuthorityYear="1962" box="[700,824,990,1015]" class="Malacostraca" family="Haustoriidae" genus="Haustorius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="canadensis">
<emphasis box="[700,824,990,1015]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">canadensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.’ In this scheme, the most common ancestor of 
<taxonomicName class="Malacostraca" family="Haustoriidae" genus="Haustorius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arenarius">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">H. arenarius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bousfield" baseAuthorityYear="1962" box="[326,491,1026,1051]" class="Malacostraca" family="Haustoriidae" genus="Haustorius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="canadensis">
<emphasis box="[326,491,1026,1051]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">H. canadensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
dated to the Cretaceous separation of the ‘Euramerican continent.’ 
<taxonomicName class="Malacostraca" family="Haustoriidae" genus="Haustorius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arenarius">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">Haustorius arenarius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
then presumably radiated into the Mediterranean Sea and across northern Europe, while ‘Genus one 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bousfield" baseAuthorityYear="1962" box="[151,275,1098,1123]" class="Malacostraca" family="Haustoriidae" genus="Haustorius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="canadensis">
<emphasis box="[151,275,1098,1123]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">canadensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’ spread down the western Atlantic coast. However, a case solely using character states does not support this, as traits such as the number of antenna 1 accessory flagellum articles, curvature of maxilla 2 outer lobe, shape of pereopod 7 article 4, and telson cleft in the Mediterranean species, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bellan-Santini" authorityYear="2005" box="[927,1068,1170,1195]" class="Malacostraca" family="Haustoriidae" genus="Haustorius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="orientalis">
<emphasis box="[927,1068,1170,1195]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">H. orientalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mulot" authorityYear="1968" box="[1122,1279,1170,1195]" class="Malacostraca" family="Haustoriidae" genus="Haustorius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="algeriensis">
<emphasis box="[1122,1279,1170,1195]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">H. algeriensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, more closely match species in the Gulf of 
<collectingRegion box="[489,577,1206,1231]" country="Mexico" name="Mexico" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">
<collectingCountry box="[489,577,1206,1231]" name="Mexico" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">Mexico</collectingCountry>
</collectingRegion>
, particularly 
<taxonomicName authority="Hancock &amp; Wicksten, 2018" authorityName="Hancock &amp; Wicksten" authorityYear="2018" box="[730,841,1206,1231]" class="Malacostraca" family="Haustoriidae" genus="Haustorius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="allardi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[730,841,1206,1231]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">H. allardi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[852,944,1206,1231]" pageId="2" pageNumber="103" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[852,944,1206,1231]" pageId="2" pageNumber="103">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
A revision of the genus, if necessary, will likely not proceed until molecular data is available to support a deep historical division.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
